<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1925-06-03T23:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1925-06-03T23:00:00-05:00" n="577" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d577">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.5045/64: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Mayer</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1925-06-04T12:00:00+08:00"><hi rend="italic">June 4,
                                        1925—noon</hi>.</date><lb/>[Received June 4—5:57
                                a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>201. Following from consul, Changsha: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>“June 3, 1 p.m. Students of all the schools in Changsha striking
                                    today because of the May 30th affray in Shanghai. Many private
                                    rikishas demolished last evening on the main streets. Boycott
                                    against British and Japanese declared. The situation is serious
                                    but is under control.”</p>
                            </quote></p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Mayer</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>